<Primer
  title="How One Gets Made"
  eyebrow="A Primer on Matter Models · Chapter Four"
  deck="A trained potential is a curve fit to a few thousand DFT readings. Where the readings come from, and how the curve is fit to them, is the whole of this chapter."
  running="Ch. 4 — How One Gets Made"
  prev={{ href: url('/primer/inside-the-network'), label: 'Inside the Network' }}
  next={{ href: url('/primer/what-mlips-keep'), label: 'What an MLIP Keeps — and Can\'t' }}
>
  <p class="lead">
    The machine has a shape. It eats a local neighborhood and returns that atom's energy; the
    pieces add to a total; differentiate the total and the forces fall out. What it still lacks are
    the values of its weights, and until those are set it returns nonsense. Setting them is what
    "training" means, and it needs two things this chapter is about: a pile of correct answers to
    fit to, and a procedure for fitting.
  </p>

  <h2><span class="num">§ 1</span>The data: a set of correct answers</h2>

  <p>
    The correct answers come from DFT — the slow, expensive method of Chapter 1 that solves for the
    electrons and reads off one energy. Each answer is a snapshot: a particular arrangement of atoms,
    frozen in place, labeled with the energy DFT computes for it and with the <strong>force</strong>
    on every atom — the slope of the energy along each direction, which DFT can also report. For a
    crystal, where the atoms sit in a repeating box, the snapshot carries one thing more: the
    <strong>stress</strong> — the way the energy changes when the repeating box is squeezed or
    stretched. Energy, forces, stress — that is one labeled example.
  </p>

  <p>
    Gather a few thousand such snapshots and you have a training set. The network is then tuned until
    its own outputs match these labels: feed it an arrangement it has seen, and it should return very
    nearly the energy and forces DFT gave for it.
  </p>

  <p>
    Which snapshots, though? This is the question that decides whether the model is any good. The
    obvious snapshots are the comfortable ones — atoms at rest, every bond at its settled length,
    every structure relaxed to a valley floor of the energy landscape from Chapter 1. They are easy
    to generate and easy for DFT to converge on.
  </p>

  <p>
    A model fit only to them fails the moment a simulation does anything interesting. Run a real
    simulation and the atoms do not sit on the valley floor; they are kicked by heat, shoved through
    the middle of a reaction, driven up the steep walls of the landscape toward the passes that
    separate one valley from the next. The model has never seen those walls, so the walls it draws
    come out too gentle: the force that should shove two crowded atoms apart is too weak, and they
    drift closer than any real material would allow. This failure mode has a name — the model has
    gone <strong>soft</strong> — and it is systematic, always toward too-little resistance, because
    the fit was anchored only where resistance was low.
  </p>

  <p>
    So the rule for the data is one word: <strong>representative</strong>. The set must cover the
    arrangements the model will actually meet at run time, and that means the uncomfortable ones —
    compressed bonds, broken bonds, half-formed bonds, atoms at the top of a pass — must be in the
    training set too, not just the valley floors. You teach the walls by visiting the walls.
  </p>

