  <h2><span class="num">§ 2</span>The loss: what "match" measures</h2>

  <p>
    "Tune the weights until the outputs match the labels" needs a precise meaning of <em>match</em>. The
    procedure needs a single number it can drive toward zero — a score for how wrong the model
    currently is, summed over every snapshot in the training set. That number is the
    <strong>loss</strong>. Training is the act of nudging the weights, over and over, in whatever
    direction lowers the loss, until it stops dropping.
  </p>

  <p>
    The obvious loss compares only energies: for each snapshot, take the gap between the model's
    energy and DFT's energy, and add up those gaps across the set. But energies alone are a trap.
    A model that nails every energy but draws the
    slopes wrong is a map with the right elevation marked at every town and the gradients between
    towns drawn backwards. Every height is correct; the map still tells you water flows uphill. It is
    useless for predicting which way anything rolls — and rolling is the entire point. A simulation
    moves atoms by following forces, step after step. Get the forces wrong and the simulation walks
    the wrong way from the very first step, no matter how right the energies were.
  </p>

  <p>
    So the loss compares forces too, term by term: for each atom in each snapshot, the gap between the
    model's force arrow and DFT's. And it compares stress, where the snapshot carries one. The three
    pieces are added with weights that say how much each matters:
  </p>

  <div class="aside"><span class="aside-label">The loss, in words</span>
    loss = (energy error) + <em>w</em><sub>F</sub> · (force error) + <em>w</em><sub>S</sub> · (stress
    error). Each error is a typical-sized gap between model and DFT — usually a root-mean-square, the
    everyday "average gap" — and the weights <em>w</em><sub>F</sub> and <em>w</em><sub>S</sub> set how
    loudly forces and stress count against energies. Because getting the slopes right is what keeps a
    simulation honest, the force weight is set high; forces are not an afterthought to the energy fit,
    they are most of it.
  </div>

  <h2><span class="num">§ 3</span>Active learning: choosing the snapshots</h2>

  <p>
    You do not know in advance which arrangements the model will meet. The atoms a simulation wanders
    into depend on the model that is driving the simulation — which does not exist yet. You need the model to find out which data you
    need, and you need the data to build the model. Each waits on the other.
  </p>

  <p>
    The way out is to bootstrap, in a loop. Start with a rough model trained on whatever data you have
    — a small, easy set, valley floors and a little more. It is not good, but it runs. Set it running
    a simulation and watch where it goes. The instant it wanders into territory unlike anything it was
    trained on, it is <strong>extrapolating</strong> — guessing past the edge of what it knows — and
    Chapter 1 said what that means: wrong, with no warning. The trick is to make it warn you anyway.
  </p>

  <p>
    One common trick — not the only one, but the clearest to explain — is a <strong>committee</strong>.
    Train not one rough model but several, each on the same data but started from different random
    starting weights, so they end up slightly different. Where
    the data is dense, all of them learned the same answer and they agree. Where the data is thin —
    exactly the arrangements you are missing — they have nothing to pin them down, so they drift apart
    and start to disagree. Their disagreement is a usable signal: it flags, atom by atom and step by
    step, precisely where the model is guessing.
  </p>

  <p>
    Now the loop closes. Wherever the committee disagrees, stop and call DFT — the slow, correct
    method — on that exact arrangement, and only there. Add the new labeled snapshots to the
    training set. Retrain. The committee now agrees in the place it used to disagree, runs further
    before it next gets lost, and flags the next gap. Repeat until it stops getting lost.
  </p>

  <p>
    The committee was the workhorse for potentials built one system at a time. Foundation models,
    trained on millions of arrangements at once, lean on related but different uncertainty signals;
    the loop is the same, only the way the model raises its hand changes.
  </p>

  <figure class="fig">
