  <h2><span class="num">§ 4</span>Foundation models: one fit for much of chemistry</h2>

  <p>
    Everything so far describes building one potential for one system — a particular alloy, a
    particular molecule. Run the loop, get a model that knows that system, and stop. The newer
    approach drops the "one system" part, and it is the approach this Almanac exists to catalog.
    Train one large model on an enormous, deliberately diverse
    pile of data — millions of arrangements spanning much of the periodic table — and you get a
    <strong>foundation model</strong> (also called a universal potential): a single fit you can pull
    off the shelf and apply to a system it was never specifically built for. For many uses it is good
    enough straight away. Where you need more accuracy on one system, you
    <strong>fine-tune</strong> — take the big pre-trained model and nudge its weights with a small
    helping of system-specific data, far less than training from scratch would take.
  </p>

  <p>
    The diversity has to come from somewhere, and it comes from a handful of large public datasets,
    each computed at its own level of DFT theory:
  </p>

  <figure class="fig">
    <table class="almanac">
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Dataset</th><th>Domain</th><th>DFT level</th><th>Rough size</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>OMat24</td><td>Inorganic crystals</td><td>PBE+U (VASP)</td><td>~110M calculations</td></tr>
        <tr><td>MPtrj</td><td>Materials Project relaxations</td><td>PBE / PBE+U</td><td>~1.58M structures</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Alexandria</td><td>Inorganic crystals</td><td>PBE / PBEsol</td><td>~5M calculations</td></tr>
        <tr><td>OMol25</td><td>Molecules</td><td>ωB97M-V hybrid (ORCA)</td><td>&gt;100M calculations</td></tr>
        <tr><td>OC20</td><td>Catalysis, adsorbates on surfaces</td><td>RPBE</td><td>~265M single points</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <figcaption><span class="fig-num">Fig. 3</span>A sample of the large public training sets behind today's foundation models. The "DFT level" column names the <em>functional</em> — the particular approximation DFT uses — that each set was computed with; the +U suffix adds a correction for transition-metal <em>d</em> electrons, and VASP and ORCA name the programs that ran the calculations. Among the crystal datasets, OMat24 holds roughly twenty times more calculations than the others combined.</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <p>
    Some models go further and train across several of these at once. UMA — Universal Models for
    Atoms — is fit jointly over five such datasets, on the order of half a billion arrangements in
    total, using an architecture that lets different parts of the network specialize — catalysis in
    one region, bulk crystals in another — without one domain drowning out the others.
  </p>

  <p>
    There is a seam under the word "universal," and it is the DFT level. A foundation model stitches
    together datasets computed with different, inconsistent recipes — PBE here, RPBE there, a hybrid
    functional somewhere else. These do not agree with each other; the same arrangement carries a
    slightly different "correct" energy depending on which recipe labeled it. Models like UMA cope
    by being told, as one more input, which recipe labeled each snapshot — so they learn several
    closely related surfaces rather than an average of contradicting ones. But the seam does not
    vanish. Ask a question that crosses recipes — a molecule meeting a crystal, each labeled at a
    different level — and the join between surfaces is real even when it is small. The model
    inherits not one DFT's mistakes, as Chapter 1 put it, but several DFTs' mistakes, each on its
    own patch.
  </p>

  <h2><span class="num">§ 5</span>Validation: does it run, not just fit?</h2>

  <p>
    A trained model reports a clean number for how well it fits: the typical gap between its energies
    and forces and the DFT it was tested against, the same root-mean-square error the loss was built
    from, now measured on held-out snapshots the model never trained on. A small error here is
    necessary. It is not sufficient.
  </p>

  <p>
    The reason is that the error is measured on frozen snapshots — single, static arrangements scored
    one at a time. A real simulation is not static. It takes thousands or millions of tiny steps, and
    at each step the model's small error feeds into where the atoms go next, which sets the next
    arrangement the model must score, which it scores with another small error. The errors compound.
    A model with an enviable static error can still, run forward in time, drift into arrangements its
    fit handles badly, feed itself worse and worse inputs, and blow up — atoms flying apart, or a
    crystal that should sit solid quietly melting on screen.
  </p>

  <p>
    So the real test is dynamic. Run the model forward for a long simulation and ask whether it stays
    <strong>stable</strong> — no explosions, no spurious melting — and whether it reproduces physical
    properties already known from experiment or from full DFT: the right melting point, the right
    stiffness, the right spacing between atoms in the crystal. A model that runs stable and matches
    those properties is trustworthy in a way a static error number cannot confirm.
  </p>

  <p>
    A model that passes both tests has earned its place. Still, everything it reports is built from
    one number and its slopes. The electrons behind the training data knew far more; how much of
    that knowledge survives into a potential is the next question.
  </p>

